WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.280
Today, you just get me for a solo episode.

00:03.280 --> 00:05.680
I have taken a lot of the questions that have come in

00:05.680 --> 00:08.040
from listeners and from people on Instagram

00:08.040 --> 00:10.440
and I'm gonna spend some time just answering questions.

00:10.440 --> 00:12.680
By the way, I just love the fact that you

00:12.680 --> 00:15.440
take such an interest in what you can do

00:15.440 --> 00:17.560
to help your kid on their education journey.

00:17.560 --> 00:18.880
I know that there's people who listen

00:18.880 --> 00:22.760
from all over the world who are never gonna set foot

00:22.760 --> 00:26.040
in an alpha school because we're not in that many places.

00:26.040 --> 00:27.440
But what I wanna do is hopefully give you

00:27.440 --> 00:29.520
a little bit of advice and maybe some ways

00:29.520 --> 00:31.200
that you can put some of the spirit

00:31.200 --> 00:32.840
of what we do at alpha school

00:32.840 --> 00:34.840
into your own homes and classrooms.

00:34.840 --> 00:35.800
So let's go.

00:35.800 --> 00:36.640
Are you guys ready?

00:38.640 --> 00:41.280
Welcome to the Future of Education podcast

00:41.280 --> 00:43.120
hosted by Mackenzie Price.

00:43.120 --> 00:46.480
Mackenzie is the founder of a revolutionary new school model

00:46.480 --> 00:49.000
that's disrupting education through AI.

00:49.000 --> 00:52.360
Join us as we discuss the latest in education innovation.

00:56.840 --> 00:58.200
All right, first question.

00:58.240 --> 01:01.480
How can I help my brilliant and bored son

01:01.480 --> 01:05.240
who is in third grade until an alpha school opens up here?

01:05.240 --> 01:07.120
Well, first of all, I have so much empathy

01:07.120 --> 01:10.360
for this question because that is exactly where I was at

01:10.360 --> 01:12.160
when I started getting frustrated

01:12.160 --> 01:13.560
with the education system.

01:13.560 --> 01:15.440
My two daughters were both really bright

01:15.440 --> 01:17.560
and they were so bored.

01:17.560 --> 01:19.960
And so that's really when people asked me

01:19.960 --> 01:21.240
like what made you start the school?

01:21.240 --> 01:25.480
I was like, I just can't watch kids sit and be bored.

01:25.480 --> 01:28.240
That said, I know that not everyone's got that option

01:28.240 --> 01:30.320
to go find a school that is awesome.

01:30.320 --> 01:33.040
However, a couple of things I would encourage you to do

01:33.040 --> 01:35.400
is look around in your town just to see

01:35.400 --> 01:38.480
if there's any other schools that are popping up

01:38.480 --> 01:40.680
that maybe could focus a little bit more

01:40.680 --> 01:43.880
on helping kids find that passion and interest.

01:43.880 --> 01:46.680
There are microschools coming up all over the country.

01:46.680 --> 01:48.400
Also tell you what I did as a mom

01:48.400 --> 01:50.960
was I made sure to kind of pack the time

01:50.960 --> 01:54.120
when I did have my kids at home with other things.

01:54.120 --> 01:57.280
So for example, we ran after school science clubs

01:57.280 --> 01:59.280
where I would invite the neighborhood kids

01:59.280 --> 02:02.240
and friends from my daughter's class to come over

02:02.240 --> 02:03.920
and we'd do just random experiments.

02:03.920 --> 02:05.400
And that was anything from like

02:05.400 --> 02:06.960
we're baking blueberry muffins

02:06.960 --> 02:09.480
to we're doing something we saw on the internet.

02:09.480 --> 02:12.200
Sometimes I would have an expert come in

02:12.200 --> 02:14.160
who was maybe another parent.

02:14.160 --> 02:16.520
I remember I had a teacher show up one time

02:16.520 --> 02:19.880
and the goal was just to make like fun experiments.

02:19.880 --> 02:22.400
I also think so many of the life skills

02:22.400 --> 02:24.120
that our kids learn are from

02:24.120 --> 02:26.480
the cool extracurricular activities that we do.

02:26.480 --> 02:29.440
But here's the key thing that I would just encourage

02:29.440 --> 02:31.400
any parent to focus on.

02:31.400 --> 02:33.360
Make sure you're connecting kids with things

02:33.360 --> 02:36.160
that they truly have a passion and interest in.

02:36.160 --> 02:37.520
Not just the things that like,

02:37.520 --> 02:40.240
hey, everybody in our neighborhood signs up for soccer.

02:40.240 --> 02:41.480
So we're doing soccer.

02:41.480 --> 02:43.600
I remember my oldest daughter,

02:43.600 --> 02:45.360
she did one season of soccer.

02:45.360 --> 02:47.760
It was quite clear she did not like soccer.

02:47.760 --> 02:50.440
And you know what, I didn't make her go do more soccer

02:50.480 --> 02:53.520
just because that's what all the kids were doing.

02:53.520 --> 02:54.360
Find those things.

02:54.360 --> 02:56.880
In fact, I have a friend who got into,

02:56.880 --> 02:59.080
her daughter was really interested,

02:59.080 --> 03:01.760
loved horses and loved archery

03:01.760 --> 03:02.920
because she'd done some archery

03:02.920 --> 03:05.400
during like a day camp she'd gone to.

03:05.400 --> 03:08.240
She ended up becoming a nationally ranked

03:08.240 --> 03:10.160
horseback archery person.

03:10.160 --> 03:11.400
I didn't even know it was a sport,

03:11.400 --> 03:14.600
but it's an example of something that is pretty cool

03:14.600 --> 03:15.440
that can be done.

03:15.440 --> 03:17.240
And so I totally feel for you.

03:17.240 --> 03:20.120
The other thing is there are some great apps

03:20.200 --> 03:23.600
that are out there where your kid could,

03:23.600 --> 03:25.560
maybe go find some things they're interested

03:25.560 --> 03:29.760
around applying math or whatever subject he's interested in.

03:29.760 --> 03:32.480
I remember when my daughter was in second grade,

03:32.480 --> 03:35.200
she got really interested in the Revolutionary War

03:35.200 --> 03:37.280
because her grandma had given her a book

03:37.280 --> 03:38.720
about the American Revolution.

03:38.720 --> 03:40.240
I had gone to the school and said,

03:40.240 --> 03:42.120
hey, could she work on a project in school?

03:42.120 --> 03:45.200
The teacher said, nope, she cannot.

03:45.200 --> 03:47.640
But I kept kind of going at it.

03:47.640 --> 03:49.200
And eventually what we did was we worked

03:49.200 --> 03:51.520
on a project at home and we got the teacher

03:51.520 --> 03:54.560
to give us 10 minutes, a whopping 10 minutes of time

03:54.560 --> 03:56.280
for her to present in front of the class,

03:56.280 --> 03:59.200
which was a fun thing for her to do as a second grader.

03:59.200 --> 04:00.520
So all that to say,

04:00.520 --> 04:02.760
I really hope we'll get an alpha to wherever you are.

04:02.760 --> 04:06.800
And in the meantime, just try to help

04:06.800 --> 04:08.560
that really brilliant kid of yours

04:08.560 --> 04:10.240
to just find things that he's interested in,

04:10.240 --> 04:11.440
excited about.

04:11.440 --> 04:13.080
Here's another thing that's actually pretty cool

04:13.080 --> 04:16.720
that I think sometimes people forget to do.

04:16.720 --> 04:19.680
YouTube is something that is such a fun thing

04:19.680 --> 04:22.680
for parents and kids to watch together.

04:22.680 --> 04:25.760
Like go watch these experiments that people do on YouTube,

04:25.760 --> 04:27.360
watch some of the challenges that they do,

04:27.360 --> 04:30.120
and do them together and then use those opportunities

04:30.120 --> 04:33.200
as a time to be able to maybe ask questions.

04:33.200 --> 04:34.440
Like, well, what would we do

04:34.440 --> 04:37.640
if we were trying to build a squirrel catching device

04:37.640 --> 04:39.920
like Mark Rober did?

04:39.920 --> 04:42.160
By the way, I got to talk with him the other day.

04:42.160 --> 04:43.000
That was pretty cool.

04:43.000 --> 04:46.520
He's gonna do some work with our science curriculum

04:46.760 --> 04:47.920
at Alpha, I know.

04:47.920 --> 04:48.760
Super exciting.

04:48.760 --> 04:49.800
He was here.

04:49.800 --> 04:50.640
He was here.

04:50.640 --> 04:51.880
I actually wanted to get him on a podcast,

04:51.880 --> 04:54.280
but I was busy and he was busy.

04:54.280 --> 04:56.480
All that to say, just find things

04:56.480 --> 04:57.480
that your kid's excited about

04:57.480 --> 04:59.800
and find ways that you and he can connect

04:59.800 --> 05:01.680
on going deeper into subjects,

05:01.680 --> 05:04.120
figuring out how to become an expert on that.

05:04.120 --> 05:06.160
Okay, this next question is from a student.

05:06.160 --> 05:07.760
And I love when I get student questions

05:07.760 --> 05:09.880
because I love the fact that there are kids out there

05:09.880 --> 05:12.600
who are saying, hey, how can I take ownership

05:12.600 --> 05:13.960
and control over my education?

05:13.960 --> 05:16.000
And so this question actually is,

05:16.000 --> 05:19.000
how can I become a student who is able to make decisions

05:19.000 --> 05:20.960
for their education on their own?

05:20.960 --> 05:22.880
Okay, I'm gonna give you a couple of examples.

05:22.880 --> 05:25.200
So at Alpha High School,

05:25.200 --> 05:28.080
we have high schools popping up throughout the country,

05:28.080 --> 05:30.680
but Austin, Texas is where our main high school is.

05:30.680 --> 05:33.800
And we've had at least four students

05:33.800 --> 05:38.000
who have reached out to me directly on Instagram

05:38.000 --> 05:41.440
and said, hey, I want to become a student at your school.

05:41.440 --> 05:45.280
And those students have gotten full scholarships.

05:45.280 --> 05:48.440
They absolutely came in and said, I'll figure this out.

05:48.440 --> 05:49.840
Let me work on this, let me get to know.

05:49.840 --> 05:51.080
They went through the interview process,

05:51.080 --> 05:51.920
they did everything.

05:51.920 --> 05:52.760
And I said, what about your parents?

05:52.760 --> 05:53.600
Do they care?

05:53.600 --> 05:54.720
And he's like, I'll work on my parents.

05:54.720 --> 05:56.400
And so their parents kind of came in

05:56.400 --> 05:58.400
towards the end of that experience.

05:58.400 --> 06:00.200
But I love the fact that I had students

06:00.200 --> 06:02.760
who reached out directly to me and just said,

06:02.760 --> 06:05.320
I want to be in an environment that helps us

06:05.320 --> 06:07.200
and how can I make that happen?

06:07.200 --> 06:09.280
And I think that's a great thing to do.

06:09.280 --> 06:11.400
And so the best thing you can do

06:11.400 --> 06:13.100
is arm yourself with research.

06:13.100 --> 06:14.540
When you're thinking about what is it

06:14.540 --> 06:16.620
that you want to do in terms of your education,

06:16.620 --> 06:19.940
maybe you're going to the local public high school

06:19.940 --> 06:23.140
and you want to transfer into another district school

06:23.140 --> 06:25.500
or you want to try one of these micro schools

06:25.500 --> 06:28.340
or maybe you want to do online or home school,

06:28.340 --> 06:30.540
come up with research that you can then present

06:30.540 --> 06:33.740
to your parents around, here's why I believe

06:33.740 --> 06:35.380
that this path is going to be best for me.

06:35.380 --> 06:37.900
And as part of that, figure out what are your priorities?

06:37.900 --> 06:39.140
What do you care about?

06:39.140 --> 06:41.020
What do you feel like you want to focus on?

06:41.220 --> 06:43.780
And I think when you present that in a way

06:43.780 --> 06:45.380
where your parents kind of understand

06:45.380 --> 06:50.380
this kid is really thoughtfully going about this decision

06:50.980 --> 06:53.180
and figuring out where the right environment

06:53.180 --> 06:54.100
is going to be for him,

06:54.100 --> 06:56.540
I think your parents will be willing to listen to you.

06:56.540 --> 06:59.020
Okay, here's another question I often get.

06:59.020 --> 07:01.660
How could I implement something like your school

07:01.660 --> 07:03.740
in my public school classrooms?

07:03.740 --> 07:06.180
So this comes from a teacher and teachers,

07:06.180 --> 07:08.100
you guys are awesome, you're absolute heroes.

07:08.100 --> 07:10.660
You know, I say it all the time, you're overworked,

07:10.660 --> 07:13.300
you're underpaid and you're underappreciated.

07:13.300 --> 07:14.860
So I love when I hear from teachers saying,

07:14.860 --> 07:17.100
how can I bring a little bit of the alpha spirit

07:17.100 --> 07:18.460
into my classroom?

07:18.460 --> 07:20.740
And I'm gonna give you a few tips of things that you can do.

07:20.740 --> 07:23.460
So first of all, motivation, in our opinion,

07:23.460 --> 07:26.440
is 90% of what creates a great learner.

07:26.440 --> 07:28.060
It's being a motivated student.

07:28.060 --> 07:31.220
And so there's a lot of different motivation mechanisms

07:31.220 --> 07:33.860
and models that you can put into your classroom

07:33.860 --> 07:35.380
that can help kids get excited

07:35.380 --> 07:37.220
and they don't have to be expensive.

07:37.220 --> 07:39.660
They can be as simple as earning stickers.

07:39.660 --> 07:42.900
And I'm telling you, we even do a sticker motivation model

07:42.900 --> 07:45.500
in our high school and our high school students get excited.

07:45.500 --> 07:47.700
My daughter, who was a senior came to me

07:47.700 --> 07:49.940
and she's like, look at this amazing super cool

07:49.940 --> 07:51.860
Taylor Swift guitar sticker that I got

07:51.860 --> 07:53.620
when I earned all my points for the day.

07:53.620 --> 07:55.660
And I remember being like, you're 18

07:55.660 --> 07:56.580
and you care and she's like,

07:56.580 --> 07:59.380
but you've never seen this Taylor Swift sticker.

07:59.380 --> 08:01.460
And it was, it was really cool to see.

08:01.460 --> 08:04.300
And so you can do a lot of different things,

08:04.300 --> 08:05.980
earning time to go do things,

08:05.980 --> 08:07.780
earning the privilege of how you work.

08:07.780 --> 08:09.020
Maybe you create a classroom

08:09.020 --> 08:12.020
where you've got like a really cool space,

08:12.020 --> 08:15.220
beanbags or something that's comfortable.

08:15.220 --> 08:19.420
And as kids get their work done and earn their privileges,

08:19.420 --> 08:21.860
they get to earn time to go work in that area.

08:21.860 --> 08:24.260
That's something we absolutely incorporate a lot.

08:24.260 --> 08:26.020
And so I think motivation is something

08:26.020 --> 08:27.900
that unfortunately traditional schools

08:27.900 --> 08:29.620
don't pay any attention to.

08:29.620 --> 08:31.340
And what are the things that you can do

08:31.340 --> 08:36.260
for individual or group motivation type of projects?

08:36.260 --> 08:38.300
That's something that I would absolutely encourage

08:38.420 --> 08:39.260
that you implement.

08:39.260 --> 08:41.420
You can even do an in-school currency.

08:41.420 --> 08:43.860
We pay our students, you can do an in-school currency.

08:43.860 --> 08:47.380
And then maybe that money that kids earn at the end

08:47.380 --> 08:51.940
earns them the ability to go do a volleyball game

08:51.940 --> 08:54.500
in the park on a Saturday morning altogether.

08:54.500 --> 08:57.380
And you figure out how to get maybe parents to chip in

08:57.380 --> 08:59.500
to bring a pizza or something like that.

08:59.500 --> 09:00.780
So there are ways to do it.

09:00.780 --> 09:03.140
It does require some creativity and extra work,

09:03.140 --> 09:07.660
which I know that you teachers already have so much of.

09:07.660 --> 09:09.380
But there's things you can do there.

09:09.380 --> 09:10.940
Here's a question from somebody

09:10.940 --> 09:13.180
who has started their own micro school.

09:13.180 --> 09:17.300
And the question is I'd love to use more AI in my micro school,

09:17.300 --> 09:19.980
but I don't know where to start.

09:19.980 --> 09:23.220
So there's two uses of AI that we're doing

09:23.220 --> 09:24.580
within our schools.

09:24.580 --> 09:27.300
The first use of AI is that we're using AI

09:27.300 --> 09:31.180
to create individualized lesson plans

09:31.180 --> 09:33.500
and provide assessment and direction

09:33.500 --> 09:35.940
for students when it comes to their academics.

09:36.140 --> 09:38.460
And we're using a lot of adaptive apps to do that.

09:38.460 --> 09:40.900
So that might be something you're thinking

09:40.900 --> 09:41.900
about trying to implement.

09:41.900 --> 09:43.660
I do have good news for you.

09:43.660 --> 09:47.060
Our time back learning platform is going to be putting out

09:47.060 --> 09:50.260
more and more software and apps

09:50.260 --> 09:55.260
that you will be able to use and download from the app store.

09:56.540 --> 09:59.860
So keep an eye out for that because it's coming.

09:59.860 --> 10:04.380
But the other way that we use AI is part of our afternoons.

10:04.420 --> 10:07.300
We're teaching kids how to use AI tools

10:07.300 --> 10:09.820
to do what we say is give them superpowers.

10:09.820 --> 10:12.380
So for example, we do public speaking workshops

10:12.380 --> 10:14.180
where our students are working on public speaking.

10:14.180 --> 10:16.780
I was just in our four year old class yesterday.

10:16.780 --> 10:17.980
We were having a parent meeting

10:17.980 --> 10:20.020
talking about some of the upcoming workshops.

10:20.020 --> 10:22.660
And we were talking about the public speaking workshop

10:22.660 --> 10:25.220
where these four year olds in six weeks

10:25.220 --> 10:26.940
are gonna be able to speak in front of an audience

10:26.940 --> 10:29.980
of 40 plus people that they don't know.

10:29.980 --> 10:32.660
And we're gonna be using some AI tools

10:32.660 --> 10:37.580
to help them with feedback on their projection

10:37.580 --> 10:40.900
and their eye contact and how they're speaking

10:40.900 --> 10:43.460
and helping them memorize the speeches

10:43.460 --> 10:45.100
that they're gonna be giving.

10:45.100 --> 10:46.980
This is all wrapped up into like a

10:46.980 --> 10:49.740
about the world culture kind of learning thing

10:49.740 --> 10:52.540
that they're gonna be able to do research with their parents

10:52.540 --> 10:54.300
about maybe where their family's from

10:54.300 --> 10:55.500
or something like that.

10:55.500 --> 10:57.580
And so they're using tools like that.

10:57.580 --> 10:59.100
Here's another thing that we're doing.

10:59.100 --> 11:01.380
We're doing a growth mindset workshop

11:01.420 --> 11:02.980
with our four year olds as well.

11:02.980 --> 11:05.740
And the test to pass at the end of the workshop

11:05.740 --> 11:09.620
is that these students will be able to complete a Lego set

11:09.620 --> 11:12.140
for 11 year old plus kids.

11:12.140 --> 11:13.420
So these are four year olds.

11:13.420 --> 11:17.020
And where we're using AI there is we're using AI

11:17.020 --> 11:19.420
to record what they say to themselves

11:19.420 --> 11:22.660
as they're going through this Lego setup process

11:22.660 --> 11:24.860
and then be able to provide coaching

11:24.860 --> 11:27.740
around how we can implement more growth mindset stuff.

11:27.740 --> 11:30.140
So if they get frustrated or if they ask for help,

11:30.180 --> 11:33.540
what are the ways that we can coach them?

11:33.540 --> 11:35.220
That's some of the stuff we're doing

11:35.220 --> 11:39.500
within our classrooms to help with building out life skills.

11:39.500 --> 11:43.060
Then there's the other part of AI usage that we're teaching

11:43.060 --> 11:46.180
is that kids can learn to do things like vibe coding

11:46.180 --> 11:50.340
to create video games or movies and videos

11:50.340 --> 11:53.100
or building out graphic novels,

11:53.100 --> 11:56.020
building art through AI tools.

11:56.020 --> 11:59.460
That is something that is gonna be such an important skill

11:59.500 --> 12:02.340
for young people to have as they go out in the world

12:02.340 --> 12:03.860
is not just the ability to know about

12:03.860 --> 12:05.740
how to use AI tools now,

12:05.740 --> 12:08.060
but how to constantly be up to date

12:08.060 --> 12:10.420
on the newest and best technology.

12:10.420 --> 12:13.260
In fact, I'm seeing this in my own job

12:13.260 --> 12:16.180
is that a tool that wasn't good two weeks ago

12:16.180 --> 12:18.060
is now suddenly so much better.

12:18.060 --> 12:21.260
So we're always helping students kind of learn

12:21.260 --> 12:22.780
how they can use AI tools

12:22.780 --> 12:24.700
in really positive and healthy ways.

12:24.700 --> 12:26.300
And that's something that you can be doing.

12:26.300 --> 12:29.700
Now, part of that requires you to also become an expert

12:29.700 --> 12:32.340
in all the latest and greatest AI tools.

12:32.340 --> 12:35.060
Here's a question that I get a lot from parents

12:35.060 --> 12:36.860
who are really worried about screen time.

12:36.860 --> 12:37.700
And this question is,

12:37.700 --> 12:41.460
how can I balance recommendations for screen time limits

12:41.460 --> 12:44.860
for four and five year olds with AI learning?

12:44.860 --> 12:46.380
Let me tell you very clearly,

12:46.380 --> 12:51.100
there are lots of differences in types of screen time.

12:51.100 --> 12:53.620
Not all screen time is created equal.

12:53.620 --> 12:55.780
So letting your kid brain rot,

12:55.780 --> 12:58.460
watching YouTube videos by themselves

12:58.460 --> 13:02.380
or watching TikTok or as a four or five year old

13:02.380 --> 13:05.700
just watching cartoons endlessly,

13:05.700 --> 13:07.380
that is something very different

13:07.380 --> 13:09.780
than giving your four year old

13:09.780 --> 13:11.900
an ability to start working on math.

13:11.900 --> 13:14.940
So for example, our four year olds in our pre-K classrooms

13:14.940 --> 13:18.580
are using Mentava to do some reading lessons

13:18.580 --> 13:20.140
that they're working on.

13:20.140 --> 13:22.020
They're also working on math apps.

13:22.020 --> 13:23.860
And what's amazing actually,

13:23.860 --> 13:26.980
is in only the first half of our school year,

13:26.980 --> 13:31.060
our four year olds have already completed their pre-K

13:31.060 --> 13:33.440
content for both math and reading.

13:33.440 --> 13:36.100
So these kids are coming in so far ahead of the game

13:36.100 --> 13:37.820
and they've still got four months

13:37.820 --> 13:39.380
before the end of the school year

13:39.380 --> 13:41.740
when they'll then graduate to be kindergartners.

13:41.740 --> 13:46.740
And so you can have your kid do 15 minutes a day of math

13:48.500 --> 13:50.760
or 15 minutes of reading and phonics.

13:50.760 --> 13:53.960
Now, one thing I do want to provide as a disclaimer,

13:53.960 --> 13:57.120
for young children, four and five year olds especially,

13:57.120 --> 14:00.120
there is nothing better than human reading

14:00.120 --> 14:01.800
and connecting and reading with your kids,

14:01.800 --> 14:04.640
making sure that they're understanding how to use phonics.

14:04.640 --> 14:06.960
So we do a lot of that at that age group.

14:06.960 --> 14:09.780
You cannot just solely rely on an AI app

14:09.780 --> 14:12.520
to teach your four year old to read.

14:12.520 --> 14:15.120
It's really important that you have that human time.

14:15.120 --> 14:17.680
But the other thing is you can also do screen time

14:17.680 --> 14:20.520
with your kids where they're working on creative endeavors.

14:20.520 --> 14:22.520
Maybe they're looking at some sort of art project,

14:22.520 --> 14:23.440
something like that.

14:23.440 --> 14:26.720
So I think the thing that I would maybe recommend

14:26.720 --> 14:30.400
as a parent is just when you hand your kid an iPad

14:30.400 --> 14:32.480
or you put them in front of a computer screen,

14:32.480 --> 14:34.480
think about what it is that they're doing.

14:34.480 --> 14:37.440
Are they sitting passively where they're just consuming

14:37.440 --> 14:42.240
content or are they engaging actively in what it is

14:42.240 --> 14:44.000
that they're working on and are they learning?

14:44.000 --> 14:45.160
That's the thing I'll think.

14:45.160 --> 14:46.440
I do know it's a hard thing.

14:46.440 --> 14:48.240
I remember when my kids were young,

14:48.240 --> 14:51.280
that's right about the time that we started having

14:51.280 --> 14:54.480
phones come out that you could watch videos on.

14:54.480 --> 14:58.600
And it felt so easy to just say, here, take my phone.

14:58.600 --> 15:02.040
And it made having dinner a little bit easier,

15:02.040 --> 15:04.000
something like that at a restaurant.

15:04.000 --> 15:07.800
I never allowed screens at dinner at home,

15:07.800 --> 15:11.600
but I definitely fell victim to it at restaurants a lot.

15:11.600 --> 15:14.640
And so these are things that we just,

15:14.640 --> 15:15.520
there's a lot of balance.

15:15.520 --> 15:17.520
But again, not all screen time is equal.

15:18.520 --> 15:20.200
That wraps up part one of this episode,

15:20.200 --> 15:22.440
but don't worry, there's a part two coming soon.

15:22.440 --> 15:24.240
Thanks for listening to Mackenzie Price

15:24.240 --> 15:26.680
and the Future of Education podcast.

15:26.680 --> 15:28.200
If you haven't hit that subscribe button,

15:28.200 --> 15:29.440
now is the time to do it,

15:29.440 --> 15:32.200
so you can stay up to date on all our episodes.

15:32.200 --> 15:34.400
You can connect with Mackenzie on social media

15:34.400 --> 15:37.200
and be part of our daily conversation over on Instagram

15:37.200 --> 15:40.120
at futureofunderscoreeducation.

